"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:4.4.2\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">4.4.2</span> Fork</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">מַזְלֵג</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(mazleg)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam2:13\">1SA 2:13</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam2:14\">1SA 2:14</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">מַזְלֵג</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(mizlgoth)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod27:3\">EXO 27:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod38:3\">EXO 38:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num4:14\">NUM 4:14</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Chr28:17\">1CH 28:17</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr4:16\">2CH 4:16</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description and usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0451_fork.jpg\" alt=\"Copper alloy fork, late 3rd–early 2nd millennium BCE, central Asia\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Copper alloy fork, late 3rd–early 2nd millennium BCE, central Asia (Metropolitan Museum of Art, CC0, via Wikimedia Commons)</figcaption></figure>The fork was used in the Tabernacle and Temple to turn sacrificial victims on the altar or to remove them. Its exact form is unknown, but it may have resembled a hook or a kind of two-pronged fork.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>For the Hebrew word <em>mizlgoth</em>, some translations (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised Standard Version (1952)\">RSV</abbr>, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised English Bible (1989)\">REB</abbr>) have “forks,” while <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr> says “hooks.” However, a more descriptive expression is recommended, such as “meat forks” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New International Version (1984)\">NIV</abbr>, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Contemporary English Version\">CEV</abbr>, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"French Common Language Version (Bible en français courant)\">FRCL</abbr>).</p>\n<p>The Hebrew word <em>mazleg</em> for fork used to describe the actions of the sons of Eli in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam2:13\">1SA 2:13</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam2:14\">1SA 2:14</a> differs slightly from the word <em>mizlgoth</em>. It is reasonable to assume that they used something ready at hand, probably the same fork used at the altar. Translators are advised to use the same word. In many languages the word used for both of these will be the same as the word for a common fork, used as an item of table cutlery.</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
